<i>Nap(p)er</i> might also have denoted a maker of table cloths, though this sense has not been recorded.","English: alternatively an occupational name from <i>Nap(p)er</i> from an unrecorded Middle English word for one who makes <i>naps</i>, i.e. drinking cups or chalices (Middle English <i>nap</i>, Old English <i>hnæp</i>). <i>Napper</i> could also be a nickname from Middle English <i>nappere</i> ‘one who sleeps or naps’, though this is the least likely of the alternatives.","American shortened form of Polish   Napierala   or a similar name."],"variants":[{"name":"Napper","meanings":["English: variant of   Napier  .","Altered form of English or German   Knapper   or of German   Nepper  ."]},{"name":"Nappier","meanings":["English: variant of   Napier  . This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Napierala","meanings":["Polish (<b>Napierała</b>): nickname for an insistent person,from a derivative of <i>napierać</i> ‘advance, press, urge’."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs William Napier was born about 1335, in Scotland. She had at least 1 son with William Napier."},"et":{"about 1335–":"umbes 1335–Surnud","1330–1401":"1330–1401","1364–1454":"1364–1454","1335–Female":"1335–Surnud","1335":"1335","1401":"1401","1454"